        "content": "**Use this ladder when a GP says ESG is integrated:**\n| Evidence type | What it tells you | Weight in underwriting |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Policy statement or PRI signatory status** | The firm has stated an intention | Low |\n| **Annual ESG report with broad KPIs** | The firm is reporting activity | Low to moderate |\n| **Sector-specific materiality map** | The GP has a framework for what should matter by company type | Moderate |\n| **Deal memo example where ESG changed price, structure, or pass decision** | ESG affected underwriting | High |\n| **Board-level ownership plan with named KPIs and accountability** | ESG affected portfolio management | High |\n| **Exit or lender diligence evidence showing the work mattered commercially** | ESG affected realized economics or process quality | Highest |\nThe lesson is simple: policies and memberships may be real, but allocators should underwrite evidence closer to the bottom of the table more heavily than evidence at the top.",
