        "content": "Power-law strategies create a distinctive evidence problem for allocators. In buyout, realized value bridges, exit history, and operating attribution can often support a relatively linear story. In venture, the distribution is noisier and the sample of truly meaningful outcomes is smaller.\nThat means allocators should ask for evidence differently.\nUseful evidence types include:\n- distribution of outcomes across portfolio companies, not just blended fund metrics\n- concentration of gross value in top winners\n- realized versus unrealized composition of the winners\n- ownership levels at entry and through later rounds\n- reserve deployment into eventual winners versus losers\n- stage-specific and sector-specific outcome patterns\nWeak evidence patterns include:\n- heavy reliance on TVPI without showing where value sits\n- emphasizing markups without showing financing context or ownership retention\n- celebrating many positive markups that are too small to matter at the fund level\n- presenting a broad portfolio narrative without identifying whether any company can realistically drive fund-level returns\nThe allocator does not need every venture manager to have a fully realized top-decile history. But they do need enough evidence to judge whether the construction and decision process are compatible with power-law reality."
