        "type": "teaching",
        "title": "Basic versus fully diluted ownership",
        "content": "One of the fastest ways for an allocator to get misled is to accept an ownership number without asking what basis it is quoted on. **Basic ownership** usually reflects current outstanding shares without fully incorporating every potential dilutive security. **Fully diluted ownership** attempts to reflect ownership after taking into account all shares and share-equivalents that are expected or potentially expected to convert into common equity, including employee options, SAFEs, notes, warrants, and other relevant instruments depending on the convention used. Why the distinction matters:\n- the same investment can appear materially larger on a basic basis than on a fully diluted basis\n- option pools and convertibles can create meaningful hidden dilution\n- a manager who quotes ownership inconsistently makes longitudinal analysis harder and can unintentionally flatter outcomes\nFor allocator purposes, fully diluted ownership is usually the more decision-useful number because it is closer to the economic claim that will matter at exit or in a later financing. That does not mean every fully diluted convention is identical."
