        "content": "Pro rata rights allow an investor to buy enough in a later financing round to maintain its ownership percentage, subject to the terms of the round and practical access. These rights matter because they can preserve a fund's economics in the rare companies that become truly important. But allocators should resist romanticizing them. A right is not the same as a result. To be economically useful, pro rata requires:\n- enough reserves in the fund to write the check\n- willingness to concentrate more capital in the winner\n- access in the round, especially if the deal is oversubscribed or allocation is politically controlled\n- internal conviction that the company is still worth supporting at the new price and terms\nThe best companies are often the most expensive to defend. That means a fund may need to commit more dollars than originally expected just to hold its percentage."
