        "title": "Start with the strategy map: private credit is a family, not a single asset class",
        "content": "A allocator starts private credit by classifying the strategy correctly. The term 'private credit' is too broad to be useful on its own.\nMajor private-credit strategy groupings include:\n- sponsor-backed direct lending\n- asset-based finance or asset-backed lending\n- opportunistic or distressed credit\n- special situations and rescue financing\n- real-estate debt\n- venture debt and growth lending\n- hard-asset or equipment-backed lending\n- specialty finance platforms with recurring origination engines\nWhy classification matters:\n- repayment sources differ materially across these strategies\n- covenant packages and lender protections differ\n- duration and liquidity profiles differ\n- portfolio construction logic differs\n- drawdown behavior in stress differs\n- performance smoothing can look similar while true underlying risk differs substantially\nAllocator implication:\nThe learner should refuse to discuss private credit in generic language. The first question should always be: what exactly is being lent against, to whom, under what structure, and with what repayment path? Without that classification step, risk assessment will remain shallow."
