        "title": "Direct lending is usually underwritten against a business, not just a coupon",
        "content": "Direct lending is often the core private credit allocation because it can offer current income, floating-rate exposure, tighter lender groups, and more negotiating influence than broadly syndicated markets. That is not enough.\nIn direct lending, the lender is typically underwriting a leveraged middle-market company whose debt must be serviced through operating cash flow and repaid through some mix of amortization, de-leveraging, sale, or refinancing. The central risk is rarely an immediate missed payment on day one.\nDay 40 established the private-credit strategy map. Day 41 narrows the lens to the largest and most allocator-relevant sleeve: sponsor-backed direct lending, especially first-lien and unitranche structures."
