        "content": "**The strongest way to read a credit agreement is to ask where value can leak and when the lender can still stop it.**\n| Document feature | What it governs | Why allocator should care |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Maintenance covenant** | Ongoing leverage or coverage tests | Creates early intervention points |\n| **Incurrence covenant** | Debt, liens, investments, restricted payments | May allow deterioration until a specific action is taken |\n| **EBITDA definition** | How leverage and coverage are measured | Can make weak credits appear safer and enlarge baskets |\n| **Baskets** | Permitted leakage, debt, investments, transfers | Small drafting changes can create large flexibility |\n| **Restricted / unrestricted subsidiaries** | Which assets sit inside lender protection | Value can move outside the collateral package |\n| **Sacred rights / pro rata protections** | What requires unanimous or broad lender consent | Determines whether lender-on-lender violence is possible |\n| **Reporting covenant** | Timeliness and detail of information | Weak reporting delays detection of stress |\nDocumentation quality should be judged as an integrated system. One strong covenant can be undermined by permissive baskets, loose EBITDA definitions, or weak amendment protections.",
