        "content": "**The income stream can look similar while the risk engine is completely different.**\n| Question | Direct lending | ABF / specialty credit |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Primary repayment source** | Borrower cash flow plus refinance or sale | Collateral cash conversion, amortization, or asset-level collections |\n| **Main underwriting lens** | EBITDA durability, leverage, docs, sponsor | Eligibility rules, advance rates, collateral behavior, servicing, structural triggers |\n| **Main hidden risk** | Earnings miss and weaker enterprise value | Fraud, ineligible assets, obligor concentration, servicer failure, weak data, warehouse fragility |\n| **What good reporting looks like** | Company operating KPIs and covenant data | Asset-level tape, dilution and loss trends, concentration by obligor, trigger history, servicing metrics |\n| **What manager edge looks like** | Origination discipline and sponsor access | Data infrastructure, collateral analytics, workout plumbing, financing access, structural design |\nThe allocator should not compare ABF and direct lending on spread alone. The question is whether the manager's team, systems, and controls fit the actual repayment mechanism.",
        "caption": "Collateral does not make ABF simple. It changes what competence looks like.",
        "whyItMatters": "This helps the learner stop using a corporate-credit template for a collateral-system strategy.",
