        "title": "Real case: Greensill showed that structure and short duration were not enough",
        "content": "Greensill-linked supply-chain-finance funds are one of the clearest negative ABF cases for allocators. The exposures were often described as short-duration, self-liquidating, and insured. But when confidence broke, the key fragilities were not the comforting labels. They were concentration, questions around underlying receivables quality, dependence on insurance, and the difficulty of converting the structure into cash once the platform failed. Tokio Marine later said policies connected to Greensill had been obtained through fraudulent misrepresentation and treated the policies as void from inception.\nAllocator lesson: in ABF, the hidden thesis may sit in a third party. If the insurer, servicer, originator, or warehouse provider is carrying too much of the risk-control burden, the LP is not underwriting only the collateral pool. It is underwriting the plumbing around the pool. That should change both manager selection and position sizing."
