        "content": "A property can look acceptable on an unlevered basis and still be a weak equity investment if the next lender will not refinance enough debt to bridge the business plan. This is why property underwriting should include a simple refinance test, not just an exit-value test.\nUseful questions include:\n- what debt yield and DSCR would a new lender require today\n- how much loan proceeds are implied by those constraints, not by sponsor optimism\n- whether extension options require new hedges, paydowns, reserve funding, or covenant compliance\n- how much time the property actually has to absorb rollover or capex before maturity\nAllocator implication:\nA deal can survive a softer exit market if the refinance is still workable. If the refinance fails, the sponsor may be forced to inject capital, sell into a weak market, or hand over control even if the property is not fundamentally broken."
