        "title": "Real-world case study: Brookfield DTLA shows how property stress becomes refinancing stress",
        "content": "Brookfield DTLA's Los Angeles office defaults are a strong allocator case because they show that a real-estate problem rarely arrives as a single-variable miss. In SEC disclosures, Brookfield DTLA described $465.0 million of debt on Gas Company Tower, including mortgage, mezzanine, and junior mezzanine loans, and disclosed that the company did not exercise an extension option, causing maturity default. The same filings also described stress around 777 Tower, including debt default tied to required rate protection, leasing-cost needs, and limited liquidity to support capital commitments.\nAllocator analysis path:\n**Step 1: identify the operating stress.** Weak office demand and rollover pressure reduced confidence in the future NOI path.\n**Step 2: identify the capital need.** The owner still needed leasing capital and time to defend occupancy.\n**Step 3: identify the refinancing break.** Debt maturities, extension requirements, and hedge obligations mattered as much as current occupancy.\n**Step 4: identify the real lesson.** A property can remain physically attractive and still become economically impaired when NOI quality, capex burden, and refinancing conditions weaken together.\nAllocator lesson:\nUnderwrite the property as a cash-flow case and a lender-behavior case. If either one fails, the equity case can unravel quickly."
